            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and sat down astonied",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘Then Daniel … was astonied or a while’. The word in the original is the same as that rendered ‘desolator’ (marg. desolate) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 9:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ‘that maketh desolate’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 11:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Here the sense of ‘bewilderment’ is uppermost. See the use of ‘astonied’ in the R.V., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 17:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
