  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I rent my garment and my mantle.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Rending the clothes was always, and still is, one of the commonest Oriental modes of showing grief. Reuben rent his clothes when his brothers sold Joseph to the Midianites, and Jacob did the same when he believed that Joseph was dead (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 37:29, 34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Job \"rent his mantle\" on learning the death of his sons and daughters (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 1:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and his friends \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "rent",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " every one his mantle when they came to mourn with him and comfort him\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 2:11, 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Rent clothes indicated that a messenger was a messenger of woe (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 1:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or that a man had heard something that had greatly shocked him, and of which he wished to express his horror (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:65",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Ezra's action is of this last kind, expressive of horror more than of grief, but perhaps in some degree of grief also. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And plucked off the hair of my head and of my beard.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " These are somewhat unusual signs of grief among the Orientals, who were wont to shave the head in great mourning, but seldom tore the hair out by the roots. The practice is not elsewhere mentioned in Scripture, excepting in the apocryphal books (1 Esdras 8:71; 2 Esdras 1:8; Apoc. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And sat down astonied.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 8:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the same verb is used in the same sense. Ezra 9:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This information threw Ezra into deep grief and moral consternation. The tearing of the upper and under garments was a sign of heartfelt and grievous affliction (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 8:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); see remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 10:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The plucking out of (a portion of) the hair was the expression of violent wrath or moral indignation, comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 13:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and is not to be identified with the cutting off of the hair in mourning ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 1:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"And sat down stunned;\" משׁומם, desolate, rigid, stunned, without motion. While he was sitting thus, there were gathered unto him all who feared the word of God concerning the transgression of those that had been carried away. חרד, trembling, being terrified, generally construed with על or אל (e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 66:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 66:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but here with ב (like verbs of embracing, believing), and meaning to believe with trembling in the word which God had spoken concerning this מעל, i.e., thinking with terror of the punishments which such faithless conduct towards a covenant God involved. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]